   <titles>
      <title>The Dilation Transformations</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The dilation transformations of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> are given by</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>D\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[n],\quad D(\Vect{x}) := s\cdot\Vect{x}</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>where <math>
                     <latex> s &gt; 1 </latex>
                  </math> is a fixed number. Thus <math>
                     <latex>D</latex>
                  </math> magnifies or dilates each vector and, therefore, each object in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math> by the factor <math>
                     <latex>s</latex>
                  </math> – hence the name ‘dilation transformation’.</para.body>
            </para>
            <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
               <img src="ims/Dilation.png"/>
            </media>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>To find the matrix representing <math>
                     <latex>D</latex>
                  </math>, we note that <math>
                     <latex>D</latex>
                  </math> transforms the basic vector <math>
                     <latex>\StdBss{j}</latex>
                  </math> into
				</para.body>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <term>of a dilation</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The matrix representing the dilation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                           </math> with factor <math>
                              <latex> s &gt; 1 </latex>
                           </math> is represented by the matrix <math>
                              <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>
                           </math>; i.e. <math>
                              <latex>s</latex>
                           </math> times the identity matrix of size <math>
                              <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
               <index.glossary>
                  <term>dilation</term>
                  <term>matrix</term>
                  <info>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>The matrix representing the dilation of <math>
                              <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                           </math> with factor <math>
                              <latex> s &gt; 1 </latex>
                           </math> is represented by the matrix <math>
                              <latex>s\cdot \IdMtrx[n]</latex>
                           </math>; i.e. <math>
                              <latex>s</latex>
                           </math> times the identity matrix of size <math>
                              <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </info>
               </index.glossary>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>D(\StdBss{j}) = s\cdot \StdBss{j} = (0,\dots ,0,s,0,\dots ,0)</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>Therefore <math>
                     <latex>D</latex>
                  </math> is represented by the matrix of size <math>
                     <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                  </math>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
s\cdot \IdMtrx[n] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{cccc}
s &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; s &amp;             &amp; 0 \\
\vdots &amp; &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; s
\end{array}
\right]
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>For example, the dilation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> in the picture above is</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
D\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2],\qquad D(x,y)=\tfrac{3}{2}\cdot (x,y) = 
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
\tfrac{3}{2} &amp; 0 \\
0 &amp; \tfrac{3}{2}
\end{array}
\right] \left[ \begin{array}{c} x \\ y \end{array} \right]
					
				</latex>
            </math.display>
         </block.body>
      </block>
